sec.p:
In Ref.~\cite{Guo:2012tm}, the Nambu-Jona-Lasinio model was generalized to deal with heavy quarks as well as light ones. The Lagrangian reads  egin{equation} %1 \mathcal{L} =  ar{\psi}({m i}
ot{\vpartial} - \hat{m}_0) \psi + \mathcal{L}_4 , \end{equation} where  egin{eqnarray} %2 \label{four} \mathcal{L}_4 &=& G_{m V} ( ar{\psi}\lambda_{m c}^{m a} \gamma_\mu \psi)^2 
otag\ && +  rac{h}{m_{m q} m_{m q^\prime}}[( ar{\psi} \lambda_{m c}^{m a} \gamma_\mu \psi)^2 + ( ar{\psi} \lambda_{m c}^{m a} \gamma_\mu \gamma_5 \psi)^2] , \end{eqnarray} describes the four-point quark-quark interaction compatible with QCD chiral symmetry. $G_{m V}$, of dimension (mass)$^{-2}$, and the dimensionless $h$ were parameters fixed in the spectral calculation. The second term on the right side in Eq.~(ef{four}) appears as {a} higher order correction expanded with respect to the constituent quark mass $m_{m q}$, similiar to the HQET expansion. We can rewrite Eq.~(ef{four}) in a Fierz invariant form. For the light sector, one has  egin{align} %3 \mathcal{L}^{m q}_4 =&  rac{4}{9}G_{m V} [( ar{q}\lambda^i_{m f} q)^2 + ( ar{q}{m i} \gamma_5 \lambda^i_{m f} q)^2] 
otag \ &-  rac{2}{9}\left(G_{m V} +  rac{h}{m_{m q} m_{m q^\prime}}ight) [( ar{q}\lambda^i_{m f} \gamma_\mu q)^2 + ( ar{q} \lambda^i_{m f} \gamma_\mu \gamma_5 q)^2], \end{align} where $\lambda_{m f}^i$'s are the $U_{m f}(3)$ generators, with $\lambda_{m f}^0 = \sqrt{\dfrac{2}{3}}I$ (where $I$ is the $3 	imes 3$ unit matrix) and the rest are Gell-Mann matrices in flavour space. For the heavy sector, one has  egin{align} %4 \mathcal{L}^{m Q}_4 =&  rac{8}{9}G_{m V} [( ar{Q}{m q})^2 + ( ar{Q}{m i} \gamma_5 \lambda^i_{m f} q)( ar{q}{m i} \gamma_5 \lambda^i_{m f} Q)] 
otag \ &-  rac{4}{9}\left(G_{m V} +  rac{h}{m_{m q} m_{m Q}}ight) [( ar{Q} \gamma_\mu q)( ar{q} \gamma^\mu Q) 
otag \ &+ ( ar{q} \gamma_\mu \gamma_5 q)( ar{q} \gamma^\mu \gamma_5 q)] , \end{align} where {we} still have  egin{equation} %5 {m Tr} \lambda_i \lambda_j = 2\delta_{ij}. \end{equation} One can see that actually we only consider the higher order $1/m_{m q}m_{m Q}$ suppressed interaction in vector and axial-vector channels and so the important chiral symmetry breaking vaccum (the ground state) is unchanged.
Using {the} Bethe-Salpeter equation (BSE), we obtained the meson masses via the corresponding $T$-matrix where the mesons appear as the poles of the $T$-matrix. The meson-quark coupling constants were also obtained by further expanding the $T$-matrix around the meson poles.
In this work, we will use the effective meson Lagrangian to calculate strong and radiative decays of vector mesons. The effective meson-quark coupling constants will be directly taken from our previous work.
In the cases of {the} pseudo-scalar meson and {the} vector meson, the corresponding effective quark couplings read  egin{align} %6,7 \L_{\uppim q} =& -g_{\uppim q}  ar\psi {m i}\gamma_5  m{	au} \psi \cdot  m{\pi} - rac{	ilde{g}_{m\uppi q}}{2m_{m u}}  ar\psi \gamma_\mu\gamma_5  m{	au} \psi \cdot \vpartial
olimits^\mu  m{\pi} , \[1mm] \L_{m \uprho q} =& -g_{\uprhom q}  ar\psi \gamma_\mu  m{	au} \psi \cdot  m{ho}^\mu. \end{align}
For the decay of a vector meson (V) into two pseudo-scalars (P), one has  egin{equation} %8 \varGamma({m V 	o PP}) =  rac{1}{2m_{m V}} \vint{m d}\phi^{(2)} | \mathcal{M}m(V 	o PP) |^2, \end{equation} where  egin{equation*} \vint{m d}\phi^{(2)} = \vint  rac{{m d}^3 k_1}{(2\uppi)^3 2E_{k_1}}  rac{{m d}^3 k_2}{(2\uppi)^3 2E_{k_2}} (2\uppi)^4 \delta^4 (q - k_1 - k_2) \end{equation*} is the standard two-body phase-space-measure. In the rest frame of the decaying meson, the decay amplitude of the vector meson can be {written} as  egin{equation} %9 \mathcal{M}({m V	o PP}) = \epsilon^\mu T_\mu = -  m{\epsilon}\cdot m{T} , \end{equation} where $\epsilon^\mu$ is the polarized vector of {the} V meson. Then we have  egin{equation} %10 \varGamma({m V 	o PP}) =  rac{k_{m c}}{24\uppi m_{m V}^2} | m{ T}|^2 . \end{equation}
The strong decay process of a vector meson is shown in {a} Feynmann diagram {in} Fig.~ef{strong}, where $$q = \dfrac{k_1 + k_2}{2} = \left(\dfrac{m_{m V}}{2}, {0}ight),~ l = \dfrac{k_1 - k_2}{2} = \left(\dfrac{k_1^0 - k_2^0}{2},~  m{k}_{m c}ight),$$ and $m_1$, $m_2$, $m_3$ denote the constituent masses of the constituting quarks. Using the Feynman rules, one can write down the expression for the decay amplitude directly. One finds  egin{align} %11 {m i} T^\mu =& - 	ext{Tr} \vint rac{{m d}^4p}{(2\uppi)^4}{m i} g_{m v} \gamma^\mu \lambda^{m V}  rac{m i}{
ot{p} - 
ot{q} - m_1}
otag\[1mm] &	imes {m i}\left(g_1 +  rac{	ilde{g}_1}{m_1+m_3} 
ot{k}_1ight) {m i} \gamma_5 \lambda^{m P_1}  rac{m i}{
ot{p} + 
ot{l} - m_3} 
otag \[1mm] & 	imes {m i} \left(g_2 + rac{	ilde{g}_2}{m_2 + m_3} 
ot{k}_2ight){m i} \gamma_5 \lambda^{m P_2}  rac{m i}{
ot{p}+ 
ot{q} - m_2} . \end{align}
For the reaction of a vector meson {that} decays into a pseudo-scalar and a photon ($\upgamma$), $m V	o P\upgamma$, the decay\linebreak\vspace{-4mm}
%fig 1  egin{center} \includegraphics{denghb-1}  igcaption{\label{strong}

}
\end{center}
\vspace{-5mm}

\noindent width can be expressed as
\begin{equation}\label{radiative}
%12
\varGamma({\rm V \to P}\upgamma) = \frac{1}{2m_{\rm V}} \vint{\rm d}\phi^{(2)} | \mathcal{M} |^ 2,
\end{equation}
where the decay amplitude should take the form
\begin{equation}
%13
{\rm i} \mathcal{M}({\rm V \to P}\upgamma) ={\rm e}
  \epsilon^\mu(V) \epsilon^{*\nu}(\gamma) T_{\mu \nu} .
\end{equation}

The Feynman diagrams of radiative decay are shown in Fig.~\ref{radi}.
We can write down the radiative decay amplitude
\begin{align}
%14
  T^{\mu \nu} =& \text{Tr} \vint \frac{{\rm d}^4p }{(2\uppi)^4}{\rm i} g_{\rm V} \gamma^\mu
  \lambda^{\rm V} \frac{\rm i}{\not{p} - \not{q} - m_1}{\rm i} \widehat{Q}
  \gamma^\nu \frac{\rm i}{\not{p} + \not{l} - m_1}  \notag\\[3mm]
  & \times{\rm i}\left (g_{\rm P} + \tilde{g}_{\rm P} \frac{\not k_2}{m_1 + m_2}\right)
 {\rm i}\gamma_5 \lambda^{\rm P} \frac{\rm i}{\not{p} + \not{q} - m_2} \notag\\[3mm]
  +& \text{Tr} \vint \frac{{\rm d}^4p }{(2\uppi)^4}{\rm i} g_{\rm V} \gamma^\mu \lambda^{\rm V}
  \frac{\rm i}{\not{p} - \not{q} - m_1} \notag\\[3mm]
  & \times {\rm i} \left(g_{\rm P} + \tilde{g}_{\rm P} \frac{\not k_2}{m_1 + m_2}\right){\rm i}
  \gamma_5 \lambda^{\rm P} \notag\\[3mm]
  & \times \frac{\rm i}{\not{p} - \not{l} - m_2}{\rm i} \widehat{Q}
  \gamma^\nu \frac{\rm i}{\not{p} + \not{q} - m_2} .
\end{align}



In the rest frame of {the} decaying meson, we only need the space components
of the tensor $T^{ij}$ and it can be written as
\begin{equation}
%15
  T^{ij} = \epsilon^{ijl}  T^l_{\rm VP\upgamma}.
\end{equation}
Then we have
\begin{equation}
%16
\varGamma({\rm V\to P}\upgamma) = \frac{\alpha k_{\rm c}}{3 m_{\rm V}^2} |T_{\rm VP\upgamma}|^2,
\end{equation}
where $\alpha \approx 1/137$ is the electromagnetic fine structure constant.

To calculate the loop integrals, we apply the three-momentum cut-off
regularization scheme to the integrals. First, we define some useful quantities
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{\rm p} (m) &=& \sqrt{\bm{p}^2 + m^2} ,\\[1mm]
E_{\rm k} (m) &=& \sqrt{(\bm{p} + \bm{k}_{\rm c})^2 + m^2} ,\\[1mm]
\omega_{1,2} &=& + q^0 \pm E_{\rm p} (m_1) ,
\end{eqnarray*}
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega_{3,4} &=& - q^0 \pm E_{\rm p} (m_2) ,\\[1mm]
\omega_{5,6} &=& - l^0 \pm E_{\rm k} (m_3) .
\end{eqnarray*}
The $\omega_i$s emerge as poles when the integral with respect to
$\rm p^0$ is performed. After we integrate out $\rm p^0$, the amplitudes can
always be represented as spatial integrals
\begin{align*}
  T =& \vint\nolimits^\Lambda \frac{{\rm d}^3 \bm{p}}{(2\uppi)^3} \sum_i^{2,4,6}
  \frac{N|_{p_0 = \omega_i}}{\prod\limits_{j \neq i} (\omega_i - \omega_j)} \\[3mm]
  =& \frac{1}{4\uppi^2} \vint\nolimits_0^\Lambda p^2{\rm d}p \vint\nolimits_{-1}^1 {\rm d}t
  \sum_i^{2,4,6} \frac{N|_{p_0 = \omega_i}}{\prod\limits_{j \neq i} (\omega_i - \omega_j)},
\end{align*}
where $N$ represents the numerator of {the} integrand. The 2-dimensional
integral will be performed numerically by {the} Monte Carlo integration
method using the {vegas} routine from {the} {gsl} library.

